5... Nxe4
{ A major alternative is   5...Bc5  6.e5  , the famous Max Lange Attack. Black has long been advised to counter in the centre, leading to quite an imbalance:  6...d5  7.exf6  dxc4  8.fxg7  Rg8  . Traditionally White checked with the rook here, but recent practice has shown that there's something likely stronger:  9.Bg5!  . Just as in our main game here, a key motif is:  9...Qd5?  Black really has to retreat with   9...Be7  , as we'll see in Line B1 of our 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 coverage.  10.Nc3!  . This exploits the pin to develop with tempo. White has unsurprisingly scored very well from here, with the hero of our last game victorious here too:  10...Qf5  11.Re1+  Be6  12.Ne4!  everything continues to come with tempo  12...Rxg7   12...Be7  13.Bxe7  Kxe7  14.Nxd4  Nxd4  15.Qxd4  also leaves White dominating  13.Nh4  Qxe4  desperation, but the queen is trapped in view of   13...Qe5  14.Nf6+  and   13...Qxg5?  14.Nxg5  Rxg5  would have seen a noted theoretician having to quickly resign in Espinosa Veloz-Mikhalevski, Internet blitz 2020, had White simply gone  15.f4  d3+  16.Kh1  Rd5  17.f5  14.Rxe4  Rxg5  15.f4  d3+  16.Kh1  dxc2  17.Qxc2  1-0, J. Christiansen-V.Moiseenko, World Rapid Championship, Moscow 2019. }
6. Re1 { Naturally White pins the knight. } 6... d5
{ Standard and fairly forced, or at least White would be delighted to see the other advance:   6...f5?  7.Bg5  rapid development once again, although a decent case can also be made for 7 Bd5  7...Be7  8.Bxe7  Qxe7  9.Nbd2  Black can't castle  9...d6  10.Nxe4  fxe4  11.Nxd4  . White will regain his pawn with interest following Bd5. }
7. Bxd5 { A little tactic to regain one of the pawns. } 7... Qxd5 8. Nc3
{ Once again White exploits the pin and so launches a double attack. } 8... Qh5
9. Nxe4 { The right way to recapture, with a certain threat. } 9... Be6 10. Bg5
{ Preventing Black's king from escaping to the queenside. White is a pawn down, but his lead in development supplies definite compensation and there's a little tactic coming up... }
10... h6
{ Black's second most popular choice after   10...Bd6  , which accepts some structural damage and will be heavily analysed in our coverage of how to counter the Two Knights Defence @@StartBracket@@1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6@@EndBracket@@.  Black can also return the pawn with   10...Bb4!?  11.Nxd4  We also spent some time analyzing   11.c3!?  dxc3  12.bxc3  Ba5  13.Nd6+!  , which is tricky and you may prefer, although after the calm  13...cxd6  14.Qxd6  Bc7!  15.Qxc7  O-O  Black has equalized, and more in the event of the greedy  16.Qxb7?  Bd5  - we want to be sacrificing pawns, not grabbing them and so ceding the initiative!  Qxd1  12.Rexd1  Nxd4  13.Rxd4  . At first sight this might look like pleasant equality for him with his bishop-pair, but...  13...Be7   13...Ba5?!  runs into  14.Nc5  14.Re1!  ...reveals that White's lead in development still counts. Now Black can't really exchange on g5:  14...Rd8   14...Bxg5?  15.Nxg5  picks up a pawn, and if  15...Ke7  16.Rde4  15.Ra4  . This still leaves Black having to be careful: for example,  15...f6  16.Bf4  a6?  17.Bxc7  Rc8  or   17...Rd7  18.Nd6+  Bxd6  19.Rxe6+  Be7  when White isn't in trouble due to a clever defense:  20.Ba5  . White has reasonable chances to unravel and gradually exploit the extra pawn after  20...Kf7  21.Re2  Rd1+  22.Be1  .  18.Nd6+!  Bxd6  19.Rxe6+  Kf7  20.Rxd6  Rxc7  21.Rb4  Re8  22.h4  . This left White a clear pawn to the good in Lorenzo de la Riva-Lillo Castany, Catalan League 2013. }
11. Bf6
{ A neat tactic to exploit the position of the black king and queen, as well as one which has caused many an opponent to go astray. }
11... Qf5
{ Played no doubt in anticipation of  12.Bxd4?  O-O-O  , but White can do much better than that. }
12. Nxd4 Nxd4 13. Qxd4 Qd5
{ Only now may it have dawned on Wang that he couldn't touch the bishop:   13...gxf6?  14.Nxf6+  Ke7  . Here White has  15.Nd5+  , and wins. }
14. Qe3
{ A calm retreat. You might have been tempted by   14.Bxg7  , but after  14...Bxg7  15.Nf6+  Kf8  Black is able to fight on. }
14... Qf5
{ Clearly the bishop is taboo due to the fork and it's extremely hard to suggest an improvement here for Black: for example,   14...Qa5  15.Rad1!  . This simply prepares Qd4 and Qd8+!, or to activate:  15...gxf6  16.Nxf6+  Ke7  17.Nd5+  Ke8  18.Qe5  . White has far too strong an attack. }
15. Qd3 { Threatening Nd6+ as the queens continue to dance. } 15... Be7
{ 15...Qd5  would have continued the dance, but...  16.Qg3  ...sees White hit both c7 and g7,  although he might also maintain the theme with   16.Qf3!?  followed by Rad1. }
16. Bxg7
{ There goes an important pawn and White isn't done yet, not by a long way. }
16... Rd8 { The best try, in view of   16...Rg8?  17.Nf6+!  Bxf6  18.Qxf5  . }
17. Nd6+ { Forcing the pace. } 17... Rxd6
{ Of course, Black can't take with the bishop and after   17...cxd6  18.Qxf5  Bxf5  19.Bxh8  he would again just be an exchange down. }
18. Qxf5 Bxf5 19. Bxh8
{ And that was that, as the bishop will make it out after   19.Bxh8  f6  20.Bg7  . }
