  9. Be3 is again also an option, and if 9...Qd8 10 Bg5 with the threat of Nb5.  9...Ng6  10.h4!  . We refuse to allow Black to settle and maintain full compensation:  10...Be7  11.g3  . This keeps the knight out of h4. The key, cramping bridgehead on e5 is secure, leaving White with pleasant, lasting compensation: for example,  11...Bd7?!   11...O-O  12.h5  Nh8  13.Qc2  forces an ugly response:  13...g6  . Here White might proceed calmly with  14.a3  .  Even   11...a6!?  12.h5  Nf8  13.h6!  g6  14.Bg5  feels a bit suspicious for Black, with such weak dark squares and White able to go Rc1 and Na4, as well as Qd2  12.h5  Nf8  13.Nb5!  a6   13...Nxe5  14.Nxe5  Bxb5  is a tactic, but:  15.Be3  not forgetting to claim a tempo and heading for d4  15...Qa6  16.h6!  g6   16...gxh6?  17.Qf3  f6  18.Qh5+  is crushing  17.Bxb5+  Qxb5  18.Bd4  Rg8  19.Rc1  . White controls the board and has far too much play for the two pawns with Qf3 next up.  14.Be3  Qa5  15.Nd6+!  Bxd6  16.exd6  Qb4  17.Bf4  . White enjoys excellent play, who is ready to go a3, as well as Ne5, and will also flick in a timely h6 to force further weaknesses. In short, Black is surely too weak on the dark squares.  Before we examine the game continuation, it should be pointed out that   7...Bc5?  8.b4!  Be7  9.b5  Na5  10.Nxd4  followed by Qg4 would leave Black badly cramped,  and that   7...Nge7  8.cxd4  Nf5  , while solid, allows White a fairly pleasant edge with  9.Bxf5  exf5  10.Nc3  Be6  This position is known to theory, but with it being Black's move, White having gone Be2-d3xf5.  11.Na4  Qd8  12.Be3  . Black has clearly lost a fair bit of time and White is also set to exert some pressure with Rc1 and Nc5; two other plans worth knowing are a3 and b4, and Ne1-d3. }
