1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. O-O Nf6 5. d4 Bxd4 6. Nxd4 Nxd4 7. Bg5
{ This pin is what attracted us to this line. White keeps the f-pawn in reserve, whereas a well-drilled or experienced opponent is much more likely to be ready for  7.f4  , quite possibly with  7...d6  8.fxe5  dxe5  9.Bg5  Qe7  , which is a fairly tough nut to crack. There's no doubt that this gambit is a good choice for fast @@StartBracket@@rapid and blitz@@EndBracket@@ games, but it is also a very good choice at classical time controls too - be that at club or even the top level! Indeed, that most creative of modern-day players, Daniil Dubov, did much to reignite interest in 7  Bg5  when he deployed it in Dubov-Radjabov, Hamburg Grand Prix 2019: }
7... d6
{ Black's most popular line along with  7...h6  8.Bh4  , as we've just considered in Line A1. }
8. f4
{ Naturally White continues with his thematic break and now Black has quite a wide choice. }
8... Be6
{ Black's main move, seeking exchanges.   In the notes to Christiansen-Bachmann, we saw that  8...Bg4  9.Bxf6  Bxd1  10.Bxd8  Rxd8  11.c3  should be OK for Black, or at least after a series of precise moves he can reach an equal if not dead endgame. }
9. fxe5 { Opening up the rook on f1. } 9... dxe5
{ This position can also arise from a 7. f4 d6 8. fxe5 dxe5 9. Bg5 Be6 move order. }
10. Na3
{ White is again happy enough to see exchanges, so long as they are exchanges on his own terms. }
10... Qe7 11. c3 { Prodding the knight. } 11... Bxc4 12. Bxf6
{ An important exchange.  12.Nxc4  Ne6  13.Bxf6  has been known to be not so accurate due to  13...Qc5+!  ever since Mestel-Szmetan, Buenos Aires Olympiad 1978. }
12... gxf6 13. Nxc4 Ne6 14. Ne3
{ A simple choice and a move which might surprise a booked-up opponent, the prophylactic 14. b4 having been White's most popular choice. }
14... Qc5 15. Qd2
{ Defending the knight and not fearing Black's next as the queen would like to slide across to f2. }
15... Rd8 16. Qf2
{ The queen slides into position. Rae1 and/or Kh1 will follow and just where is the black king going to find safety? }
16... Ng5 17. Rae1 Nxe4 18. Qh4
{ Talk about ideal coordination for White. All Black has going for him is the pin and two extra pawns, which is nowhere near enough in view of }
18... Nd6
{ 18...Ng5  19.Rxf6  Rg8  20.Rf5!  Qe7  21.Qh5  is also rather effective. } 19.
b4 Qc6
{ 19...Qb6  20.Kh1  followed by  Nd5  or  20...c6  21.Qxf6  Kd7  22.Nf5!  should also be crushing.    And now in Holzke-Maze, Biel 2011, }
20. c4
{ would have left Black getting absolutely squashed.    We actually can't resist mentioning how the game ended:   20.Rxf6!?  Qe4?  The ice-cool   20...Qxc3  21.Nd5  Nf5!  would fight on after  22.Nxc7+  Qxc7  23.Rxf5  .  21.Ng4!  Qc4  22.Rff1  f5  23.Rxf5!  Nxf5  24.Nf6+  1-0. }
