{ A critical choice as Black goes two pawns to the good. } 6. Re1
{ The pin ensures that White will quickly regain a pawn. } 6... d5
{ Very much the normal choice.   6...f5?  7.Bg5  Be7  8.Bxe7  Qxe7  9.Nbd2  is just too risky for Black, as we saw in the notes to Li Chao - Wang Yu.   And after  6...Be7?  7.Rxe4  d5  8.Rxe7+!  Nxe7  9.Bb3  c5  10.c3!  White's minor pieces should prove somewhat more powerful than Black's additional rook, not least in the event of  dxc3  11.Nxc3  d4?  12.Ng5!  O-O  13.Qh5  , which would already be pretty much decisive. }
7. Bxd5
{ A little tactic to regain the pawn and speed up White's development. } 7...
Qxd5 8. Nc3 Qd8
{ Retreating to base is Black's third most popular.   By far his main choices are, however  8...Qa5  9.Nxe4  Be6  10.Bd2  .   And  8...Qh5  9.Nxe4  , the subject of Line B22. }
9. Rxe4+
{ At last we see White preferring to recapture with the rook! Why now? Well, the rook adds to the pressure against  d4  and here  9.Nxe4  Be7  10.Bg5  is fairly well met by  10...f6  when White doesn't have any tactics }
9... Be7 10. Nxd4
{ It's high time to regain our final bit of the gambitted material. } 10... f5
{ This bold advance is critical and the only real way of making sense of the queen retreat.   10...Nxd4?  11.Rxd4  Bd7  12.Bf4  left Black horrifically tied down and unable to castle in Marshall-Esser, London 1899.   10...O-O  11.Nxc6  bxc6  wrecked Black's structure in Tartakower-Billecard, Ostend 1907, where one route to a pleasant edge was  12.Qxd8  Bxd8  13.Rc4  Bf5  14.Be3  -remembering that it's what stays on the board that counts, not what goes off - just think of your Fischer-Petrosian classic!-  14...Bxc2  15.Rxc6  followed by  Rc1  and possibly  Nd5  . }
11. Rf4
{ Keeping everything secure. An unprepared player might worry about such a move, but it's a much better choice than  11.Rxe7+?  Nxe7  12.Qh5+  Ng6  ,   while after  11.Bh6!?  fxe4  12.Bxg7  Kf7!  13.Bxh8  Qxh8  14.Qh5+  White only has enough play to force a draw. }
11... O-O
{ Invariably played.   11...Bd6?!  12.Nxc6  bxc6  13.Rd4  would suddenly recentralise the rook }
12. Nxc6
{ Naturally White takes the opportunity to shatter Black's structure. } 12...
Qxd1+ 13. Nxd1 bxc6 14. Ra4
{ Trying to tie Black to the defence of a7 while preparing to complete development with Bf4 and Ne3. }
14... g5 15. Bd2
{ The plan is Bc3 and Ne3-c4. Black can try to disrupt this but after   15...Rd8  16.Bc3  f4  White can free his knight with  17.f3!  Bc5+   17...Bf5  18.Nf2  Bxc2  19.Rc4  regains the pawn in view of  19...Rd6?!  20.Bb4  and White should always keep a timely, disruptive advance of Harry, as well as Re1 and Ne4 ideas in mind.  18.Nf2  Bf5  19.h4!  creating some potentially useful luft while reminding Black that his extended kingside can become a target. Play might continue  19...h6  20.Kf1  Bxc2  21.Rc4!  looking fairly promising for White, and if  21...Bxf2?!  22.Kxf2  Rd6  23.hxg5  hxg5  24.Rc5  Rg6  25.Rh1  when the opposite-coloured bishops are most certainly favouring the side with the initiative - White. }
