1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ The solid Petroff Defence. These days your opponent is likely to be either expecting the main line with  3.Nxe5  d6  4.Nf3  Nxe4  5.d4  d5  6.Bd3  or here the fashionable  5.Nc3  variation, but White has another aggressive choice, and one with plenty of grandmaster supporters. }
3. d4
{ Perhaps surprisingly this direct central challenge is seen some four and a half times less than  3.Nxe5  on the database, and is even somewhat less common than  3.Nc3  .  We did, of course, give some consideration to the Cochrane Gambit, but unfortunately after  3.Nxe5  d6  4.Nxf7!?  Kxf7  , while White does have some compensation for the piece, he doesn't lead in development, which is something we strive to do throughout this repertoire. }
3... exd4 { A pretty natural choice, but very much Black's second choice. } 4.
e5 { Naturally White is quite happy to press ahead with tempo in the centre. }
4... Ne4
{ Invariably played, in part because the alternatives simply leave Black in some trouble.   Likewise, White should welcome  4...Nd5  5.Qxd4  Nb6  6.Nc3  Nc6  7.Qe4  Be7  8.Bf4  . This kept  Bd3  in reserve to prepare  O-O-O  , which left White somewhat the more active in Cubas-Deus Filho, Ponta Grossa 2017. }
5. Qxd4
{ The main line. As it gives White good, active development and every chance of obtaining the advantage, we won't shy away from it, but if you want to surprise your opponent, you could do far worse than   5.Qe2!?  . Here  5...Nc5  6.Nxd4  Nc6  7.Be3  is quite pleasant for White, who will quickly castle queenside   but what about  5...Bb4+?  Well, yes, there is that, but then  6.Kd1!  forces Black to find  6...d5!  7.exd6  f5  to remain afloat.  At club level we can imagine plenty of opponents quickly going astray here, but unfortunately after  7...f5  White doesn't have anything better than  8.Nbd2  Bxd2  9.Nxd2  O-O  10.dxc7  Qxc7  11.Qc4+  , which should only be about equal. }
5... d5
{ Black supports his knight and threatens  6...Bc5  , thereby pretty much compelling White to capture en passant. }
6. exd6 Nxd6 7. Nc3
{ Knights before bishops, to keep Bobby Fischer happy and enable White to consider castling on either side. }
7... Nc6
{ Black usually can't resist copying so.   After  7...Nf5?  8.Qxd8+  Kxd8  9.Ng5  Nd6  10.Nb5  his position was already creaking in Klovans-Gousseinov, Arvier 2004. }
8. Qf4
{ First played by Chigorin and Napier back in 1896, this choice later received Kasparov's seal of approval against Karpov and is very much White's main move, keeping the queen in touch with Black's kingside. }
8... g6
{ Black's most popular choice, activating his dark-squared bishop, but there are a number of important alternatives. And now we can return to the sharpest line, 8...g6: }
9. Be3
{ The most active square for the bishop and one which also rules out any issues with ...Qe7+. }
9... Bg7 10. O-O-O
{ Naturally with Black having castled short, White would like to attack. }
10... O-O 11. h4
{ Here comes Harry... White wastes no time trying to strike a blow on the kingside, although it should be said that if you're happy with positional pressure, a good alternative is  11.Bc5  followed by  Bb5  , exploiting the pins to the maximum. }
11... Be6
{ Black's joint most common response in practice, but it badly underestimates White's attack.   Once again, there's no need to worry about  11...Qf6?!  :  12.Qxf6  Bxf6  13.Nd5  Bd8  14.Bh6!?  Re8  15.Bg5  , which still leaves Black under pressure on the kingside.   Or  11...Bxc3?  12.bxc3  h5  @@StartBracket@@Schulze-Horbach, correspondence 2003@@EndBracket@@  13.Bc5  . White isn't so much after winning a pawn on d6, as keeping Black under pressure while he launches a strong attack. That may happen after Bd3 and Ng5 or:  13...Be6  14.c4!  when the simple but deadly threat is once again Ba3-b2. }
12. h5 { Unsurprisingly it's a case of full steam ahead on the kingside. }
12... Qf6 13. Qh2
{ It's not every day that you get to double on the h-file by move 13! White's queen has gone on quite a journey via d4 and f4 to reach h2 and already the attack is simply very strong. }
13... Rfe8
{ Likewise,  13...gxh5?!  14.Qxh5  Qg6  has been tried, but after  15.Qc5!  a rather large threat is simply  Bd3  . }
14. hxg6 hxg6
{ Already there's no real defense, as we can see too from  14...Qxg6  15.Bd3  f5  16.g4!  followed by  Rdg1  . }
15. Bg5
{ Forcing the black queen up the board while setting up a strong sacrifice. }
15... Qf5 16. Rxd6 cxd6 17. Bd3 Qa5
{ 17...Qg4  makes no difference - with the knight on  d6  eliminated,  18.Ne4  is simply a killer. }
18. Ne4 Nb4 19. Qh7+ Kf8 20. Qh8+
