1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. d4 Nxe4
{ Black's most popular choice when he is likely to be expecting 4. Bd3... } 4.
dxe5
{ Our favorite capture and one which may gain you some time on the clock, it being about six times less popular than the main line,  4.Bd3  . }
4... Bc5 { Clearly the critical move, if not one for the faint-hearted. } 5.
Bc4
{ White wastes no time teeing up play against f7 and now Black has to tread quite a narrow path. }
5... Nxf2
{ Greedy, and best.   We saw back in Almasi-Giri that  5...Bxf2+?  6.Kf1  would be pretty unwise for Black }
6. Bxf7+ Kxf7 7. Qd5+ Kg6 8. Qxc5
{ It's high time to remove the bishop and keep forcing the pace. } 8... Nxh1 9.
Nc3
{ We should remember that White is now threatening not just Qc4 and Nh4+, but also Nd5. }
9... h6
{ The best defense.   We saw in Almasi-Giri that  9...d6?!  10.Qc4  leaves Black walking a tightrope,   but he can transpose to our main line here with  9...Nc6  10.Qc4  h6  11.Nd5 }
10. Qc4
{ It makes sense to relocate the queen and harry Black. You may also wish to consider the move order  10.Nd5!?  when play transposes below after  10...Nc6  11.Qc4   and  10...Kh7  11.Qc4  ,   while giving Black the chance for  10...d6?!  which would take us back into the realm of Almasi-Giri after  11.Qc4  . }
10... Nc6 { This brave move was Levon Aronian's recent choice. } 11. Nd5
{ White introduces the threat of  11.Nh4+  Kh7  12.Qe4+  Kg8  leaves nothing better than the repetition with  13.Qd5+  Kh7  14.Qe4+  , etc. }
11... d6 { Accurate defence. } 12. e6
{ A familiar motif to keep Black bottled up. Instead, White repeated moves with  12.Nf4+  Kh7  13.Qd3+  Kg8  14.Qd5+  , etc, in Nepomniachtchi-Aronian, Skilling Open @@StartBracket@@rapid@@EndBracket@@ 2020, but at that point Nepo was one up with only one game left in the second set of their quarter-final match. }
12... Kh7 13. Qe4+ { An important check. The e-pawn needs support. } 13... Kg8
14. e7
{ Pushing on before Black can blockade then begin to untangle after ...Ne7. }
14... Qe8 15. Be3
{ Another precise move, first mentioned by Lakdawala in his 'The Petroff Defence' where he thought 'Black stands only slightly worse'.  Should White cash in immediately with  15.Nxc7  Black has  15...Bf5!  , and if  16.Qd5+  Qf7  17.Nxa8  Qxd5  18.e8=Q  Kh7  when in view of Black's very active pieces White has to force a draw with  19.Ng5+!  hxg5  20.Qh5+  Kg8  21.Qe8+  , etc. }
15... Bd7 16. Nxc7 { It's time to cash in before Black simply goes ...Rc8. }
16... Qxe7 17. Qxe7 Nxe7 18. Nxa8
{ Taking stock, White has regained the rook, but in view of his own trapped knight, he should only emerge slightly for choice, as is the case after  18...Kf7  19.Nc7  Rc8  20.Bxa7  Rxc7  21.Kd2  Ng3  22.hxg3  Nf5  23.Bf2  While the g-pawns are doubled, one of them is an extra pawn and White can aim to combine playing actively  (Rf1 and g4-g5)  with an advance of his queenside majority, probably best begun with b3 and c4. }
