4. Nf3
{ Immediately pressuring  e5  .  4.axb4  Bxb4  5.c3  might look tempting with Evans Gambit-type play, but after  5...Be7  6.d4  d6  , and if  7.Nf3  Nc6  , Black's position is pretty solid. }
4... Nc6 { Natural and almost invariably played. } 5. Bb2
{ A resource not available to White in the related position after 1 e4 e5 2 Nf3 Nc6. Here   5.Bc4  isn't totally ridiculous either, but after  5...Nf6  White likely needs to proceed fairly slowly, as  6.Ng5?!   6  d4?  exd4  7.O-O  Nxe4  not really working when there's no Nc3 resource.  is well met by  6...d5  7.exd5  Na5 }
5... Qb6
{ Black's most ambitious choice, hoping to deflect the bishop from b2 after a trade on a3. It's far from obligatory though. }
6. Nxe5
{ Slightly to our surprise this is yet to be tested, but if this is too ambitious for you, you may be pleased to know that the slower  6.Bd3  d6  7.O-O  has been preferred in a couple of fairly high-level correspondence encounters. }
6... bxa3 7. Bc3
{ White is now ready with all of Nxa3, the diagonal-clearing Nc4 and even Qh5, so Black is now likely to be consistent and go... }
7... a2
{ ...with the point that  8.Rxa2?  Nxe5  9.Bxe5  Qe6  forks bishop and rook and even  10.Ra5  b6  11.Rd5  f6  works out rather well for Black, as shown by Rotella. }
