1. e4 c5 2. b4 cxb4 3. a3 bxa3
{ And so we finally come to the proof of the pudding as Black accepts the gambit, leaving White with compensation in the shape of his centre, the open a1-h8 diagonal and pressure down the a-file. }
4. d4
{ White tends to recapture on a3 with a piece, but there's no reason not to take over the centre without delay. }
4... d6
{ Black usually reacts in Pirc or Black Lion fashion so, but it's far from forced. }
5. Nxa3 { Only now does White recapture, preparing a timely Nb5. } 5... Nf6
{  } 6. Bd3 { Simple development, shoring up e4. } 6... Nc6
{ Black continues to develop in the centre, at least for now. } 7. c3
{ Yet again White is happy to shore up d4 while keeping the black knight out of b4. }
7... g6 8. Ne2 { Our standard development. } 8... Bg7 9. O-O {  } 9... O-O 10.
f4
{ Thus far play has been quite principled from both sides. White's strong centre again supplies definite compensation and Black must either suffer passively or react in the centre. }
10... d5
{ Black's main choice in the limited practice so far, as he is again seduced by an invasion of e4. }
11. e5 { Naturally White seizes the space on offer. } 11... Ne4 12. Bxe4
{ Forcing things, but the unhurried  12.Nc2!?  and if  12...f5  13.c4  e6  14.Ne3  can very much also be considered. }
12... dxe4 13. Ng3 f6 14. exf6
{ A new try. White regained his pawn with  14.Be3  b6  15.Nxe4  in Pijpers-De Ruiter, Wijk aan Zee 2016, where  15...Na5  16.c4  Bb7  gave Black enough play on the light squares to maintain a rough balance. }
14... exf6 15. f5
{ The point of White's play, spurning the pawn for now to cramp the black kingside. }
15... Bxf5 16. Nxf5 gxf5 17. Nc4
{ Only again White can do much better than allow Black to untangle with  17.Rxf5?  Ne7  and ...d5. He is now ready to go Ba3 and Nd6, or Ne3, when the arrival of a knight on f5 will certainly keep Black on his toes and leave White with lasting pressure and compensation. }
