1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Qb6
{ Finally, we can return to the main line of the Advance French. } 6. Bd3
{ The most active square for the bishop as White prepares to sacrifice the d-pawn. }
6... cxd4
{ After  6...Bd7  White can, of course, simply transpose to our main variation after  7.O-O  when Black doesn't really have anything better than taking on  d4  .   It has to be said that both Lc0 and AllieStein were happy to disrupt and develop with  7.dxc5  Bxc5  8.O-O  in the recent Top Chess Engine Championship @@StartBracket@@TCEC@@EndBracket@@ }
7. O-O Bd7
{ Normally played. As we saw in Carlsen-Harikrishna  7...dxc3  8.Nxc3  just leaves White with easy development and compensation. }
8. Re1
{ The dangerous attacking Swedish GM Jonny Hector's pet line, simply overprotecting  e5  . Don't forget that this is actually a rare position in this repertoire where you have a choice - Magnus Carlsen having made a decent case for the somewhat rarer  8.Nbd2!?  in Carlsen-Harikrishna   8.cxd4  Nxd4  9.Nxd4  Qxd4  10.Nc3  would be the old main line of the Milner-Barry. }
8... Nge7 { Black's most common response, beginning to develop the kingside. }
9. h4
{ The choice of Hector and Jones. White simply wants to dissuade  ...Ng6  . Once again the old-school  9.cxd4?!  Nxd4  10.Nxd4  Qxd4  11.Nc3  doesn't really convince after  11...a6!  ,   But it is possible to follow in Carlsen's footsteps with  9.Nbd2  when  9...dxc3  10.bxc3  Rc8  11.Nb3  Qc7  12.h4!?  would be Carlsen-Harikrishna once again. }
9... h6
{ Black's main move in the limited practice thus far, preventing any ideas of Ng5, as well as h5-h6. }
10. Nbd2
{ Again we quite like this Carlsenesque approach. It should be noted that Hector initially went  10.h5  ,  (before switching to 10. Na3; neither approach is exactly terrible.)   But we feel that White can do better, be that with the text or even the engine-approved  10.a3!?  , simply angling to seize space with  b4  . }
10... dxc3 11. bxc3 Na5
{ This makes sense, eyeing c4 and freeing c6 for the other knight. } 12. Ba3
{ An improvement over the  12.Nb3  of Lopez Gracia-Villuendas Valero, Zaragoza 2017, where Black might just have gone  12...Nec6  . }
12... Rc8 13. Rc1
{ 13.Rb1  Qd8  14.Nb3  is also pretty logical, but we quite like the calm text move, simply defending the c-pawn, preparing  c4  and emphasising how it's not so easy for Black to free his position. For example: }
13... Nec6 14. Bxf8 Kxf8 15. c4 dxc4 16. Nxc4 Nxc4 17. Rxc4
{ sees White making active use of his 13th move and not fearing exchanges with }
17... Nb4 18. Qd2
{ as Black's tangled-up kingside remains a major feature of the position. Indeed, Lc0 is loving White's compensation and chances, and no surprise when you consider such lines as  18...Nxd3  19.Rxc8  Bxc8  20.Qxd3  g6  21.h5  g5  22.Rc1  Kg7  23.Nh2 }
