1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Bd7 6. Bd3
{ Continuing to follow our favourite and simple development scheme against the French. }
6... cxd4 7. O-O
{ Offering a pawn for a certain lead in development as White hopes to quickly build on the space advantage generated by his bridgehead on e5. }
7... dxc3 8. Nxc3 Nge7 9. Bg5 a6
{ Black is alert to the rather large threat of Nb5. } 10. Re1
{ Shoring up the key, cramping advanced e-pawn and even allowing White to consider sacrificial ideas with Nxd5 exd5; e6 if Black is careless. }
10... h6 11. Bh4
{ It's tempting to maintain the pin, but there's a good reason why we advocate   11.Be3  as our repertoire choice. }
11... Nb4
{ It's notable how often Black is tempted by this leap in such positions. Here it's far from bad, but there was also   11...g5!?  12.Bg3  Bg7  when White doesn't have enough for the pawn, in part because ...Nf5 is now a strong concept. }
12. Bb1 Qc7
{ Not the greatest square for the queen.   12...g5  13.Bg3  Rc8  would have been a better use of the open file and after  14.a3  Nbc6  Black would have remained for choice, as shown by  15.h4  Bg7!?  the calmer   15...g4  16.Nd2  h5  is also promising  16.hxg5  hxg5  17.Nxg5  Nf5  18.Bf4  Nce7  when White is suddenly faced with an attack on the kingside. }
13. Bg3 { Bringing the bishop back into play while allowing Harry to advance. }
13... Rc8 14. h4 { Thematically preparing to harass ...Ng6 with h5. } 14... g6
{ 14...g5?  15.hxg5  hxg5  16.Nxg5  would now have only left the black king rather exposed with Qf3 a big threat.  However, there was no need to touch the g-pawn and   14...Nbc6  15.Bd3  Na5  followed by ...Nc4 might have left Black slightly for choice, albeit with everything still to play for in this rather complex position. }
15. h5
{ Hector knows no fear and typically plunges into complications, but a decent case might have been made for the calmer   15.a3  Nbc6  16.Bd3  followed by Bf4 and Rc1, which would ideally tee up b4 and Qd2 to follow. }
15... gxh5
{ The German IM is up to the challenge and avoids the obvious   15...g5?  on account of  16.Nh2!  , which isn't just a thematic retreat in such a position, but also a pretty strong one, as shown by  16...Bg7  17.Ng4  Qb6  18.Nf6+  Bxf6?  19.exf6  , leaving the knight on e7 badly short of a good square. }
16. Nh2
{ Even here White was right to rely on this retreat. Will he now manage to get in Qxh5 and Ng4? }
16... Rg8 17. Qxh5 Rg5
{ The immediate   17...Qc4!?  might have been more accurate, and if  18.Bh4  Nbc6  when  19.a3  Nd4!  20.Rd1  Ng6  21.Bg3  Ba4  would still have left Black's nose in front. }
18. Qh3 Qc4 { Again preventing Ng4, but now White can gain a useful tempo. }
19. Bh4
{ 19.f4  would likely have also netted the exchange, but after  19...Rxg3!  20.Qxg3  Nf5  Black would again have enjoyed a fair amount of activity in return for it. }
19... Rh5
{ Possibly Renner was put off   19...Rg8!  by  20.Ne2  with the threat of b3, but after  20...Nc2  21.Bxc2  Qxc2  22.Ng4  Rxg4!  23.Qxg4  Rc4  Black would have taken over the initiative and enjoyed promising play for the exchange. }
20. g4
{ 20.Ng4!  Bg7  21.Qg3  was the calm way to go when even  21...Kd8!?  22.a3  Rxh4  23.Qxh4  Nbc6  24.Qg3  wouldn't this time have left Black with quite enough for he exchange with Bd3 and Nf6 on their way. }
20... Rxh4 21. Qxh4 Nf5
{ A strange decision. Did Renner simply forget about the sleeping bishop on b1?  Instead,   21...Nd3!  22.Bxd3  Qxd3  23.Rad1  Qc2  24.Re2  Qh7  would have remained extremely unclear with neither king completely happy. }
22. Bxf5 exf5 23. Qh5
{ Possibly this was the short move Black missed. Suddenly there's absolutely nothing good to be done about the huge threat of e6. }
23... d4
{ If   23...Be6  24.gxf5  or   23...Kd8  24.Qxf7  Bc5  25.e6  Be8  26.Qxf5  , which simply must be crushing. }
24. e6 Bxe6 25. gxf5 Rc5
{ This doesn't help, but clearly neither would have   25...dxc3  26.fxe6  cxb2  27.Qxf7+  Kd8  28.Qd7  . }
26. Ne4
{ There are simply too many threats and, of course,   26.Ne4  Rxf5  27.Qxf5!  Bxf5  28.Nd6+  would be a double check. }
